metadata.name: Dencity #225
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.

metadata.name: VOYAGERS #217
metadata.description:
Generative animated painting made from looping gestures in a virtual void.

Voyagers is an exploration of automated gestures and screenspace layering effects. Each brush stroke sweeps through the canvas leaving a trail of color that either disappears or mixes with adjacent colors. The image slowly builds up to achieve an equilibrium between the rhythm of the gestures and the interaction of color values. These colors are quantized and dithered to produce chunky, textured, blocks of light that reify the materiality of the screen and the pixel. Two aspect ratios are possible, each with its own material relationship to screen-based work, 1:1 and 4:3 (vertical).

Press 's' to save looping animated GIF (live mode only).
Press 'p' to pause the animation.
Press 'c' to capture a single frame.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: Giants of the Meadow #100
metadata.description:
For my first drop on the new fxhash v1.0 I wanted to make something different. So I challenged myself to write a raymarcher like the ones I use in my shaders but in p5.js and make a fully procedural scene with it. It's a bit tricky to work with vectors once you are used to GLSL, but I managed to write a decent algorithm that scans a grid and slowly draws the image. It draws it with circles and triangles for the grass. The first thing I used for testing was a SDF of a plane with some tall bars on it. Then I was trying different distortions on the shapes and in one moment the results gave me the idea of a scene with mushrooms and grass on an undulated terrain. Later I added a small river and a cloudy sky. I think I was inadvertently inspired by some children's books I had when I was a kid. 

Best viewed full screen.

Features:

Mood: happy - normal - melancholic - strange - sleepy
Mushrooms: 2 - 4 (sometimes one of the mushrooms can only be seen on full screen)
Mushroom height: short - medium - tall
Mushroom fatness: S - M - L - XL
Mushroom shape: 1 - 2 - 3- 4 - 5
Mushroom tilt
Flowers color: white - yellow - pink - cyan - multicolor
River: yes - no
Camera orientation: north - south

metadata.name: Solace #66
metadata.description:
Solace is an algorithm that generates artworks of sand dunes. It draws hundreds of thousands of tiny points according to a probability distribution calculated from the positions of the dunes.

The logic to divide the dunes into light and dark sides is simple, but produces some interesting chaotic behaviour. These are details that weren't hard-coded but emerge organically, such as the patterns on the spines of the dunes or the stripes around their bases.

Please note that the algorithm can take some time to run, especially when the number of dunes is high.

Created by lunarean.

metadata.name: The Golden Ratio #3
metadata.description:
In the footsteps of Euclid, Adolf Zeising and Leonardo Fibonacci. The golden number Phi 1.6180339. 

The beginning forms a square, which is divided with the rules of the golden ratio. The partition is done on the left, right, top or bottom side. Where to divide, is decided by chance.Two rectangles are created. The process repeats. The rectangles are partitioned again according to the described rules.

The algorithm allows between 6 and 250 divisions. The number of the divisions is also random. With just 6 divisions an image of 4096 possible variants is created. At only 20 divisions there are 1,099,511,627,776 variants.

There are 29 different color palettes. After the division a random assignment takes place. A color palette consists of at least 4 colors. Which color each of the rectangles gets, is again decided by chance.

Features:
* 29 color palettes
* 5 division levels
* 4 background colors
* black/white grain

By pressing the numbers 1-4 on the keyboard, the image can be saved in a resolution up to 8K.

metadata.name: monopole #52
metadata.description:
Physics is, above all, beautiful.

Inspired by all the things I find beautiful in physics, and the nostalgia I feel for my undergraduate days of learning about the universe. I sought here to explore what can be created with simple graphics showing simple physical systems. 

The vector field shown is the field from a collection of monopoles, such as electrons and positrons or hypothetical magnetic monopoles.

The papers and inks available are those I have on my desk.

A 2400x2400 download of the image can be generated by pressing UP, but this will take several minutes. An SVG download can be made by pressing DOWN and is suitable for plotting (or laser cutting).

metadata.name: Quantum Vacuum #669
metadata.description:
Empty space is not empty. It's filled with energy, transient fluctuations in quantum fields, bubbling with virtual particles popping in and out of existence. 

Part of an ongoing series of work combining my fascination with the fringes of fundamental physics, the emergence of complex behaviour through the interaction of very simple rules, and my obsession with hacking our perceptual systems. 

/Disclaimer: This is not a simulation, but an artistic conceptual interpretation and dramatization. :)

metadata.name: Metropolis IX #52
metadata.description:
We divide spaces into smaller spaces which we conquer and live in our solitude. We call that Metropolis.

Started this piece as a rule based generative art. Simply the algorithm takes a rectangle and throws 2 random points inside it within defined x and y distances. Then using those 2 points, algorithm draws another rectangle and assigns letters to the corners of rectangle "A,B,C,D" starting from top left corner in clockwise direction. Then it starts to draw cells from inner rectangle's corner A to parent's corner A and goes on. Once 4 cells are created, it creates 4 more cells in between other cells, thus dividing a rectangle into 9 pieces. This is where "IX" comes from. Depending on the cell properties; algorithm assigns circles, triangles, lines and points to cells creating a city scape when certain parameters are given to the division algorithm.

There are 18 possible outcomes:
"Hazy Day" 13% probability (half of this style will come with slightly more color transition)
"Hazy Night" 10% probability
"Crystal Day" 11% probability
"Crystal Night" 5% probability
"Mondrian Day"  3% probability
"Mondrian Night" 3% probability
"Bauhaus Day" 3% probability
"Bauhaus Night" 3% probability
"1 Chroma Day" 4% probability (Multiple values of a single hue on a monochrome gradient)
"Mondrian Crystal Day" 3% probability
"Mondrian Crystal Night" 3% probability
"Monochrome Day" 3% probability 
"Monochrome Night" 4% probability 
"Vibrant Day" 12% probability
"Vibrant Night" 9% probability
"Rainbow Day' 5% probability
"Rainbow Night' 3% probability
"Chaotic Day"   3% probability (which takes pretty random parameters and 25% of this outcome has probability of creating very first coloring style of the project, see console for the hidden feature)
